00:00:55.690 --> 00:00:55.690
Stan?

00:01:05.070 --> 00:01:07.640
Good morning.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:12.990
This morning we're going to talk about
human interface design principles.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:23.010
Human interface design principles
are basically statements of

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:28.080
policy about designing interface
that work most of the time,

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:31.620
and that's gained from
concrete experience.

00:01:31.620 --> 00:01:36.880
But as I was thinking about how to
gel the concept of HI principles down,

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:39.800
I thought I'd illustrate
it with a riddle.

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:46.080
This riddle is about three salespeople
in your organization who are on a

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:48.800
trip trying to sell your software.

00:01:48.870 --> 00:01:52.470
And they get done with their
job late at night and they

00:01:52.470 --> 00:01:54.790
have to check into a hotel.

00:01:54.800 --> 00:01:59.150
Turns out it's a very inexpensive hotel,
but they have to get up early

00:01:59.150 --> 00:02:00.800
the next morning for a flight.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:03.980
So as they're preparing,
as they're on their way up to

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:08.800
the room with the bell person,
they ask him, "How much is the room?"

00:02:08.830 --> 00:02:10.400
And he tells them,
"It's $30." I told you

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:11.800
the room was cheap.

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:15.800
So that meant that they each
gave him $10 for the room.

00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:18.640
Well,
the bell person takes the money back

00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:24.110
down to the clerk and the clerk says,
"The room is only $25.

00:02:24.290 --> 00:02:27.150
You've overcharged them by $5."

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:29.870
So the clerk on the way back,
the bell person on the

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:31.700
way back up is thinking,
"I don't know how to split

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:36.550
$5 evenly three ways."

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:42.260
He gives them back one dollar per person
and puts two dollars in his pocket.

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:45.000
So let's see what we've got so far.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.540
They each paid $9 to the room,
that's $27.

00:02:48.550 --> 00:02:52.740
The bell person kept $2, that's $29.

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:54.780
Where did the other dollar go?

00:02:55.540 --> 00:02:58.420
Now it's early in the morning hopefully
and at least some of you aren't

00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:00.940
quite sure where that dollar went.

00:03:00.990 --> 00:03:05.430
And the reason that you're not thinking
about this problem right is I created

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:10.090
an expectation in you by telling
you something that wasn't true.

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:13.200
I told you that each person
paid $9 for the room,

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:15.320
and that was $27.

00:03:15.470 --> 00:03:18.560
And in doing that,
I created an expectation in you

00:03:18.690 --> 00:03:23.640
that led you to think about the
problem in a particular way.

00:03:23.780 --> 00:03:28.200
As a matter of fact,
each person paid $8.3 for the room,

00:03:28.310 --> 00:03:34.510
$2/3 for the tip, that's $27,
they each got back $1, that's $30.

00:03:35.290 --> 00:03:39.810
But by mismanaging your expectations,
I cause confusion in you.

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:44.960
When we create interfaces,
we don't intend to confuse people,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:46.200
but we may.

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:51.580
And so, HI principles are about setting
and managing expectations that

00:03:51.670 --> 00:03:54.200
help the user use the software.

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:57.200
And that's what we're going
to talk about this morning.

00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:59.200
Why are they important?

00:03:59.310 --> 00:04:05.790
Well, first of all, the user benefits.

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:11.480
Applying these principles will
make your software more usable,

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:15.440
and that turns out to be one of
the top predictors of satisfaction.

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:19.060
So of course you want satisfied users,
applying these principles

00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:20.540
will help you get there.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:23.200
In addition,
think what happens when they can't

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:25.320
use a particular piece of software.

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:26.730
What do they do?

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:30.600
After they've exhausted
the manual and help,

00:04:30.690 --> 00:04:34.650
if they go there at all,
what they're going to do next is go find

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:39.600
someone else in their organization that
they think knows how to use the software.

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:41.710
And that person is going to sit
down with them and they're both

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:46.300
going to start working to figure
out how to solve the problem.

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:51.680
At that point in time you have two
people who aren't doing their job.

00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:58.010
Turns out that that costs a lot of
money and lost productivity each year.

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:02.350
So you want to set the right
set of expectations so that

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:07.740
users can learn the product,
they can work well with it and get their

00:05:07.950 --> 00:05:10.570
work done without losing productivity.

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:13.700
And what's that mean for you?

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:16.530
That means that you're
going to spend less money.

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:19.380
It's going to reduce your support costs.

00:05:19.490 --> 00:05:23.000
It's going to simplify and, therefore,
reduce the amount of documentation

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:24.400
that you have to produce.

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:27.500
And in addition,
you're going to produce less UI.

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:31.670
As we go through the principles,
you're going to see that an application

00:05:31.670 --> 00:05:35.040
with less UI is actually a better one.

00:05:35.150 --> 00:05:37.820
And that, of course,
is going to lead to revenue.

00:05:38.190 --> 00:05:41.350
So this is a win-win situation.

00:05:41.350 --> 00:05:43.200
Now there are a lot of principles.

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:45.350
Don't memorize this chart.

00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:47.520
This is just to give you an idea
of the ones that we're going to

00:05:47.550 --> 00:05:49.980
spend a little bit of time on today.

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:53.920
There's one that's very big and
we'll spend particular time on

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:56.140
that one to get things started.

00:05:57.150 --> 00:06:03.210
But these principles are documented in
the Aqua Human Interface Guidelines.

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:04.700
They are available on the web.

00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:07.090
If you don't have a copy, download it.

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:07.980
It's free.

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:13.030
And the early part of that will deal
with the human interface principles,

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:16.650
and the rest of the document
shows how we've extended those

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:21.250
principles and actually created a UI,
and it tells you how to use them.

00:06:21.430 --> 00:06:25.890
And a lot of that will be the topic
of what will be in the next session.

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:30.090
So the first principle
is know your users.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:34.560
And if you haven't heard it before,
you are not your user.

00:06:35.140 --> 00:06:40.410
You have to find out who they
are and what they can do.

00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:45.300
and you have to find out what they're
doing because uh... they come in

00:06:45.300 --> 00:06:47.520
all sorts of different flavors and

00:06:48.950 --> 00:06:52.790
What you learn about them will
help you create a user interface

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:55.380
that meets their expectations.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:59.550
And kind of a rule of thumb that we use,
and you can adapt it however you want,

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.140
is pick your favorite victim.

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:07.000
Could my niece, my nephew, my mom,
my dad, my kid, and my favorite one,

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:10.500
the irritating neighbor,
for those of you from California,

00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:13.000
if you've seen the Pac Bell commercials,
you know about the guy next door

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:18.590
that comes over to borrow your DSL,
could that guy use your interface?

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:24.700
One way to identify who your
users are and what they can do

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:26.760
is to create a usage scenario.

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:31.840
Simply set down in writing
or in a document by examining

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:34.380
your users who they are.

00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:39.680
For example, is it a child in school
using their first computer?

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:42.880
Is it an ex-Windows user?

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:45.460
Is it a person creating
a professional movie?

00:07:45.660 --> 00:07:49.620
All of them come to the interface
with different expectations.

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:50.620
And what are they doing?

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:52.540
Are they creating a website?

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:56.160
Are they creating a family tree?

00:07:56.800 --> 00:07:59.490
Are they creating a movie,
as I suggested?

00:07:59.620 --> 00:08:02.020
Again,
this will determine what they think

00:08:02.020 --> 00:08:04.690
about when they approach the interface.

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:08.810
And their background and what they
have to do will also determine how they

00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:11.850
approach the task and the interface.

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:16.320
So the time you spend getting
to know them will allow you to

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:22.500
adapt the interface to their
particular skills and expectations.

00:08:23.070 --> 00:08:26.660
And when you do that,
keep in mind that what you're going

00:08:26.660 --> 00:08:31.360
to be doing is taking their job,
what they want to do,

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:33.960
and making it easier for them to do that.

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:36.740
So you're not just going to go and say,
"They do this, then this, then this,

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:38.920
then this," and mimic
it in the interface.

00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:42.430
You want to find out what they're doing,
think about how can you make

00:08:42.560 --> 00:08:47.310
them get their work done better,
and then that's what you'll do.

00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:50.600
We tend to think of users
as falling on a dimension.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:53.700
On one end we have what
we call the low end users.

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:58.040
Typical of that would be the person
who has a new mini-DV camera and says,

00:08:58.140 --> 00:08:59.300
"I really like that iMovie.

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:03.620
I want to use it." And they go out
and buy their very first computer.

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:08.260
They would be a relatively low skilled
group in terms of using a computer.

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:12.220
Another example might be the children in
school that are handed an iBook and said,

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:14.930
"This is what you're going
to do your homework on."

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:19.400
On the other end of the spectrum we
have what we sometimes call power users.

00:09:19.530 --> 00:09:22.500
These are the very
sophisticated scientists,

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:28.560
professional designers, IT professionals,
the ones that tend to use what we

00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:30.810
sometimes call the high-end apps.

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:37.490
But keep in mind that that new user,
the so-called newbie,

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:40.920
is going to learn over time
and become more proficient

00:09:41.090 --> 00:09:45.450
in performing certain tasks,
particularly the tasks that are

00:09:45.450 --> 00:09:47.970
involved in getting their work done.

00:09:48.820 --> 00:09:54.230
And the high end user, the power user,
they really become masters at

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:58.780
the applications that are used
in getting their work done.

00:09:58.910 --> 00:10:01.340
But when they use a
new piece of software,

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:06.120
even though they may bring more
sophisticated approaches to using it,

00:10:06.250 --> 00:10:09.300
they're still novices
at that point in time.

00:10:09.860 --> 00:10:14.010
Both of these groups are going to
be very frustrated if they can't

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:19.590
get their work done because yours
or our software gets in their way.

00:10:20.250 --> 00:10:22.700
So, know your users.

00:10:22.740 --> 00:10:26.270
Fundamental basis for all
the rest of the principles.

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:30.650
The next principle is kind of the
basis for graphical user interface.

00:10:30.650 --> 00:10:33.300
We're calling it C and point.

00:10:33.330 --> 00:10:38.000
Basically it says that everything a
user can do is visible in the interface.

00:10:38.100 --> 00:10:40.200
And in particular,
there's a model that says,

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:42.440
first I pick an object,
and then I pick a verb

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:44.140
to act on that object.

00:10:44.140 --> 00:10:48.350
And that's the basic model
of graphical user interface.

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.820
They can pick the action
in a couple of ways.

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:53.540
And we'll discuss direct
manipulation in a minute.

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:56.410
But the most classic way
is to select an object,

00:10:56.410 --> 00:11:01.360
as you see here, selecting the folder,
and then selecting an action

00:11:01.390 --> 00:11:03.890
to perform on that object.

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:07.470
And the idea is that the user
doesn't have to know any syntax.

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:11.000
They don't have to know,
they don't have to memorize any commands.

00:11:11.010 --> 00:11:13.150
It's all visible to
them in the interface.

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:15.810
We mention this because we still
see some applications that don't

00:11:15.810 --> 00:11:18.080
quite get the principle right.

00:11:18.240 --> 00:11:22.360
For example, they might ask someone
to pick a property,

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:25.220
then pick an object,
and then pick something else that causes

00:11:25.220 --> 00:11:27.280
the property to be applied to the object.

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:30.030
And it gets complicated
and confuses the users.

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:34.400
So that's a basic fundamental principle,
C and point.

00:11:35.460 --> 00:11:36.530
Metaphors is another one.

00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:40.520
You can take real world objects and use
them as a metaphor in the interface.

00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:42.860
For example,
menus are something that people

00:11:42.860 --> 00:11:44.750
are familiar with in restaurants.

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:47.240
They know they can pick
items from a menu to,

00:11:47.240 --> 00:11:49.790
in the case of a restaurant, choose food.

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:51.970
We can take that,
put it in the interface,

00:11:51.970 --> 00:11:54.580
and help them out by
something that's familiar.

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:58.400
They know how to manage files
and folders and coordinate them.

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:02.940
So we can use that knowledge and
build folders into the interface.

00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:06.220
They know that they can use a
trash can to throw things away.

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:11.240
So we know that we can create
a metaphor on the computer as

00:12:11.300 --> 00:12:14.960
a way of getting things off the
computer or throwing it away.

00:12:16.530 --> 00:12:24.280
So metaphors allow us to take real world,
familiar objects and take advantage

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:28.750
of what the users already know about
those objects in getting work done.

00:12:28.900 --> 00:13:02.200
[Transcript missing]

00:13:02.370 --> 00:13:05.610
But in the early days when
people created their work,

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:08.610
saved it on a diskette,
they weren't very comfortable

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:12.800
about taking that diskette then
and putting it in the trash can.

00:13:12.850 --> 00:13:15.010
You know,
I don't want to throw my work away.

00:13:15.150 --> 00:13:17.460
And you'll notice, by the way,
in MacÂ OSÂ X now,

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:20.660
I don't think many of you
use diskettes anymore,

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:25.580
but if you drag a CD around
or a zip disk around,

00:13:25.580 --> 00:13:29.060
you'll see that the trash can
turns into an icon of the eject

00:13:29.150 --> 00:13:33.460
button to help people who have
trouble with that metaphor.

00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:38.100
So metaphors, use them,
but put some thought behind how

00:13:38.100 --> 00:13:40.640
you use them in the interface.

00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:43.700
The next principle is
Direct Manipulation.

00:13:44.290 --> 00:13:48.260
Whenever possible,
let the user act on the object the

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:50.640
way they would in the real world.

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:54.600
It saves them having to scan
the menus to find something.

00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:58.060
In this case, for example,
what's illustrated is taking

00:13:58.120 --> 00:14:02.200
a file and dragging it and
dropping it into a folder.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:04.580
In fact,
drag and drop is probably the most

00:14:04.580 --> 00:14:07.120
common form of direct manipulation.

00:14:07.230 --> 00:14:10.400
And when you use drag and drop,
try to use it, you know,

00:14:10.630 --> 00:14:14.800
wherever you use copy and paste,
use it for dragging files around,

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:16.910
but use it for other things as well.

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:23.190
Like if a user selects text,
let them drag the text around.

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:25.320
In general,
you want to use direct manipulation

00:14:25.320 --> 00:14:27.220
wherever it's expected.

00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:30.980
And users actually expect it more
than just moving things around.

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:33.280
So support it whenever they use it.

00:14:33.400 --> 00:14:39.670
In this example, we have a text document
and we have the color

00:14:40.070 --> 00:14:43.760
A little chip from the color
picker is being dragged around.

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:48.640
The chip knows something about its color,
maybe the color space it came from.

00:14:48.770 --> 00:14:52.570
The text document knows that it can
take information from that chip,

00:14:52.570 --> 00:14:56.630
that is the color that it wants,
and change the text to that color.

00:14:56.790 --> 00:15:01.790
Another example would be if you
used a name and an address book

00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:05.510
that contains phone numbers,
email addresses, all sorts of things,

00:15:05.510 --> 00:15:07.980
but you could drag it into
some other application,

00:15:08.010 --> 00:15:11.560
and that application would know
that it could take from what

00:15:11.560 --> 00:15:14.750
was being dragged information
that it needed about the user.

00:15:14.870 --> 00:15:18.510
Not all of the information,
just the pieces that

00:15:18.630 --> 00:15:20.860
apply to that application.

00:15:20.980 --> 00:15:25.430
The best way to see what users
expect is to observe them.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.520
The next principle is Flexibility.

00:15:29.630 --> 00:15:36.500
Let different users at different
times do things in different ways.

00:15:36.810 --> 00:15:41.950
I've listed seven possible
ways of selecting a verb,

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:43.410
for example, here.

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:46.320
Now,
we're not suggesting that every single

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:48.230
case you use all seven of these.

00:15:48.310 --> 00:15:49.800
That would be horrible.

00:15:49.940 --> 00:15:52.810
But for example,
if there's a very frequently

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:56.560
accessed menu command,
give it a keyboard shortcut.

00:15:56.660 --> 00:15:59.090
Don't give all of your
commands keyboard shortcuts.

00:15:59.210 --> 00:16:02.600
That overwhelms the user,
and they never remember them anyway.

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:06.830
