00:21:13.790 --> 00:21:17.080
Okay, the next principle is
called User Control.

00:21:17.290 --> 00:21:20.530
Basically,
the user should drive the computer,

00:21:20.530 --> 00:21:23.170
the computer should not drive the user.

00:21:23.510 --> 00:21:25.790
So you want to make sure that the

00:21:26.470 --> 00:21:30.100
You're providing an environment where
the user feels that they have control

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:32.540
over what's happening in the computer.

00:21:33.370 --> 00:21:35.840
One way to do that is make sure
you don't send them down a path.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:41.340
For example,
a calendar application might say,

00:21:41.340 --> 00:21:45.580
allow the user complete control
on when to pick the people,

00:21:45.660 --> 00:21:52.900
the place, the time,
and there was another aspect of the

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:56.410
calendar which I'm forgetting right now,
but the point is, rather than say,

00:21:56.430 --> 00:21:59.700
do this, then this, then this,
it allows the user to do

00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:01.340
it in any order they want.

00:22:01.360 --> 00:22:04.420
Now, sometimes...

00:22:05.890 --> 00:22:09.220
You do want to assist the user by
providing them a sequence of steps.

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:11.040
We do that with assistance.

00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:14.950
But always we allow the user to
change the things that they're setting

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:17.240
up in the assistant in other ways.

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:18.800
So the user needs to be in control.

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:22.240
Now one way of doing that,
because there are times when there

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:26.760
are things that they can't do at
the interface in a particular time,

00:22:26.790 --> 00:22:30.980
is to show,
to enable or disable UI in order to tell

00:22:31.230 --> 00:22:33.280
them that something isn't available.

00:22:33.410 --> 00:22:34.630
But it's not gone.

00:22:34.690 --> 00:22:35.990
It's still there.

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:38.200
So that's an example.

00:22:38.270 --> 00:22:42.920
The other way is provide
a warning or an alert,

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.910
particularly if the user is
about to do something horrible.

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:48.400
If they want to, for example,
trash their hard disk,

00:22:48.500 --> 00:22:50.570
that's their right.

00:22:50.830 --> 00:22:54.460
Give them a warning, but let them do it.

00:22:54.790 --> 00:22:58.220
And then the other thing is
to provide a working context,

00:22:58.320 --> 00:23:01.240
such as a set of tool palettes
that are appropriate to the

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:03.520
task being done at the time,
so the user doesn't

00:23:03.520 --> 00:23:04.530
have to hunt for them.

00:23:04.620 --> 00:23:07.670
They feel they're in control
of the system because the tools

00:23:07.670 --> 00:23:11.070
they need are always present
at the time they need them.

00:23:11.200 --> 00:23:13.630
Toolbars is an example.

00:23:13.790 --> 00:23:17.390
These are favorite things that the
user wants to access frequently,

00:23:17.420 --> 00:23:20.600
and we can sit here and decide
for the user what those are,

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:25.390
but better is letting the user decide
what they are and be able to tailor the

00:23:25.390 --> 00:23:31.130
menu bar in terms of the actions that
they're going to do most frequently.

00:23:32.730 --> 00:23:37.190
The next principle, Consistency,
is sometimes overemphasized,

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:41.700
but please don't underestimate
how important this principle is.

00:23:41.800 --> 00:23:45.500
This is probably the fundamental
principle that allows users to build

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:49.700
up an expectation of how a system
works or how an application works.

00:23:49.810 --> 00:23:57.410
In this example behind you, or behind me,
we were showing an example where

00:23:57.410 --> 00:24:00.800
if you drag an icon from the dock,
we show a little poof icon.

00:24:00.960 --> 00:24:05.720
And the user learns that that means
that the item is gone from the dock,

00:24:05.720 --> 00:24:08.110
but not gone from the system.

00:24:08.270 --> 00:24:10.800
Well, to build on that experience
and to be consistent,

00:24:10.890 --> 00:24:13.480
we do the same thing
in toolbars elsewhere.

00:24:13.480 --> 00:24:16.880
Here in the System Preferences,
for example, if you drag the icon off the

00:24:16.960 --> 00:24:20.760
toolbar in System Preferences,
you see the poof.

00:24:20.950 --> 00:24:25.140
And by consistently doing that,
consistently using that metaphor,

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:29.800
the user learns that this is
how -- this is what it means.

00:24:30.040 --> 00:24:33.070
It means the item's gone
from wherever I took it from,

00:24:33.070 --> 00:24:35.070
but it's not gone from the system.

00:24:37.420 --> 00:24:41.680
Consistency is a difficult one,
so when you think about it,

00:24:41.820 --> 00:24:45.300
consider whether or not you
need to be consistent with,

00:24:45.300 --> 00:24:46.930
for example, your application itself.

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:49.810
Now, that's, I think,
is actually a fairly important one.

00:24:50.020 --> 00:24:55.220
It's often the case that we can
identify the timeline of development

00:24:55.230 --> 00:24:59.130
of a major application or the
organizational structure of a large

00:24:59.130 --> 00:25:02.400
company that produces applications
just by looking at how differently

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:06.290
things are done in different places.

00:25:06.580 --> 00:25:09.820
This allows everybody to be creative,
but it also confuses users.

00:25:09.850 --> 00:25:13.970
Users are then not sure,
how do I accomplish this goal

00:25:14.120 --> 00:25:19.500
here when in another place
it's done in another way.

00:25:19.500 --> 00:25:23.340
Another element to consider is
if you're building an application

00:25:23.390 --> 00:25:28.540
that's based on some concept
or model from the real world,

00:25:28.580 --> 00:25:30.590
either in terms of the real world
or something that you did in a

00:25:30.690 --> 00:25:34.440
previous version of your application,
or applications that are

00:25:34.440 --> 00:25:38.600
similar to yours do it,
at least consider whether you want

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:43.610
to break that expectation that the
user has by being inconsistent.

00:25:43.610 --> 00:25:45.690
Because if you are,
you may make it difficult

00:25:45.690 --> 00:25:47.450
for them to use your product.

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:50.910
And finally,
this is going to keep coming up,

00:25:50.990 --> 00:25:52.890
the Aqua Human Interface Guidelines.

00:25:52.940 --> 00:25:57.820
It's very important to be
consistent with what you see in the

00:25:57.820 --> 00:26:00.640
guidelines that are provided in the
Aqua Human Interface Guidelines.

00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:06.070
The reason is the user is going
to build up expectations based on

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:09.840
their interaction with the operating
system and other applications

00:26:09.840 --> 00:26:11.700
that have followed the guidelines.

00:26:11.700 --> 00:26:15.450
If you don't follow the guidelines,
then not only will users have

00:26:15.450 --> 00:26:19.050
difficulty using your application,
but this will break down their

00:26:19.050 --> 00:26:22.380
expectations that they've built
up from the operating system and

00:26:22.380 --> 00:26:29.490
other applications and will lead
to possibly confusion in general.

00:26:31.220 --> 00:26:32.890
What you see is what you get.

00:26:33.110 --> 00:26:34.980
Very well known principle, WYSIWYG.

00:26:35.130 --> 00:26:37.030
It has two aspects.

00:26:37.130 --> 00:26:39.630
And in terms of output,
I wanted to point out that it

00:26:39.640 --> 00:26:43.020
was originally talked about
primarily in terms of printing.

00:26:43.140 --> 00:26:47.390
But we're now creating all sorts of
different media that we then send to

00:26:47.390 --> 00:26:50.980
some other--we create something on the
computer and send it to other media.

00:26:51.110 --> 00:26:52.570
For example, we create movies now.

00:26:52.580 --> 00:26:55.860
We put them on DV or QuickTime.

00:26:55.990 --> 00:27:01.900
We create music and it goes on
iPods or in games or other places.

00:27:01.900 --> 00:27:04.050
And pictures that go on albums.

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:08.120
In all cases,
what the user sees or hears or

00:27:08.120 --> 00:27:13.360
possibly sometime in the future smells,
what's on the computer should be the

00:27:13.360 --> 00:27:18.520
same thing that they experience in
the final media that it's taken to.

00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:22.960
The other aspect of what you
see is what you get has to

00:27:22.960 --> 00:27:25.470
do with the interface itself.

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:30.800
What the user needs to get the task
done should be visible to the user.

00:27:30.800 --> 00:27:37.510
They should always be able to find
all the functionality of your product.

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:41.340
Now you don't necessarily want to show
all the functionality at the same time,

00:27:41.390 --> 00:27:44.040
but always make it obvious
to the user how to get to

00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:46.030
the additional functionality.

00:27:48.870 --> 00:27:51.670
And now I'm going to ask
Pat to demo User Control,

00:27:51.680 --> 00:27:55.640
Consistency,
and What You See is What You Get.

