00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:06.820
The next principle I want to talk
about is Feedback and Communication.

00:31:06.890 --> 00:31:10.780
This is essentially the computer
gives information to the user,

00:31:10.810 --> 00:31:13.500
the user makes requests of the computer.

00:31:13.550 --> 00:31:16.660
And there's various ways to do that,
but the one I want to emphasize

00:31:16.660 --> 00:31:22.420
now is to use your main window,
the primary interface,

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:24.300
as much as you can.

00:31:24.300 --> 00:31:24.300
Don't

00:31:24.620 --> 00:31:27.130
Users don't like to have to
go off to dialogues or other

00:31:27.240 --> 00:31:28.550
places to get things done.

00:31:28.750 --> 00:31:32.170
So in this example here,
I have a mail window and I made a

00:31:32.190 --> 00:31:36.910
request in the mail window to see all
the mail that has in the body of its

00:31:36.910 --> 00:31:40.620
text the word "special." And I made
the request in the primary interface.

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:43.710
I didn't have to go to a dialogue
to say that's what I want.

00:31:44.070 --> 00:31:48.660
In addition,
the mail app is giving me back the

00:31:48.660 --> 00:31:51.040
results in the primary interface.

00:31:51.230 --> 00:31:54.690
Again, I don't have to go someplace
else to see what the results are.

00:31:54.700 --> 00:31:59.080
So here we see the number of hits
and they're ranked in terms of

00:31:59.080 --> 00:32:03.500
likelihood of being what I was
looking for based on that word.

00:32:03.830 --> 00:32:05.440
So it's using the primary interface.

00:32:05.490 --> 00:32:09.960
That's what I want to emphasize
as much as possible as opposed to

00:32:10.030 --> 00:32:12.560
sending the user somewhere else.

00:32:12.740 --> 00:32:15.810
And the users want to
know what's going on.

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:20.480
So always provide status and progress.

00:32:20.640 --> 00:32:23.730
The worst thing in the world is when the
user just hits a key and then sits there,

00:32:23.800 --> 00:32:25.940
"What's happening now?

00:32:26.050 --> 00:32:29.340
I don't know." There are times
when you may want to get the user's

00:32:29.340 --> 00:32:32.450
attention in the application,
and if you're not the

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:36.980
frontmost application,
use our notification system because

00:32:36.980 --> 00:32:42.580
we will gently and subtly get the
user's attention by bouncing the icon

00:32:43.340 --> 00:32:48.440
When you do have to tell the user there's
something wrong or get their attention

00:32:48.440 --> 00:32:53.190
when you are the frontmost application,
use a good error message,

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:55.200
and I'll talk about that in a second.

00:32:55.200 --> 00:32:59.200
The other thing I wanted to say is
don't bury the user in dialogues.

00:32:59.360 --> 00:33:05.260
Again, the worst thing is when a user
gets a modal dialogue to do this,

00:33:05.280 --> 00:33:07.260
and then the next thing they have
to do is get another modal dialogue,

00:33:07.260 --> 00:33:09.180
and then another modal dialogue,
and then they have to back

00:33:09.190 --> 00:33:10.200
all the way out again.

00:33:10.310 --> 00:33:12.200
So try to keep that as flat as possible.

00:33:12.200 --> 00:33:18.840
I would say never more than two levels,
and the best is one or none.

00:33:20.420 --> 00:33:23.860
When you write an alert,
use our standard alert.

00:33:23.870 --> 00:33:26.240
You need to provide your
application's icon because we

00:33:26.240 --> 00:33:30.470
have a new window layering model,
and they have to be able to keep

00:33:30.470 --> 00:33:34.400
track of what application is
telling them that there's a problem.

00:33:34.400 --> 00:33:38.190
In addition, if you use a standard alert,
you'll have a place where you use

00:33:38.190 --> 00:33:43.880
the large system font to kind of
summarize briefly the condition or error

00:33:44.160 --> 00:33:48.460
that you need to alert the user to,
and then in small system font,

00:33:48.460 --> 00:33:53.300
you can give them a fuller description,
the consequences of the condition,

00:33:53.320 --> 00:33:54.980
and how to get out of it.

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:57.770
And then finally,
providing them meaningful push

00:33:57.770 --> 00:34:02.980
buttons where it's very clear exactly
what to do to correct the situation.

00:34:06.340 --> 00:34:09.300
So, we all know this one, forgiveness.

00:34:09.300 --> 00:34:12.120
The worst thing in the world is when
the user does something that they didn't

00:34:12.120 --> 00:34:16.820
intend to do or they do something and the
result is not what they intended to do.

00:34:16.820 --> 00:34:20.510
And they're sitting there saying,
"Now what?

00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:24.570
I'm in trouble." The principle of
forgiveness says you're going to give

00:34:24.570 --> 00:34:26.460
them a way to deal with the problem.

00:34:26.530 --> 00:34:28.750
One way to do that is to
track the steps visually,

00:34:28.750 --> 00:34:31.340
and I'd like to call attention
to one of my favorites.

00:34:31.340 --> 00:34:33.490
I think it's a very good
example of user forgiveness,

00:34:33.490 --> 00:34:36.530
and that's the history
palette in Photoshop where

00:34:36.530 --> 00:34:44.240
you can undo an awful lot of,
in my case, terribly egregious mistakes.

00:34:44.240 --> 00:34:48.310
So, and in other cases,
let the user exit a sequence

00:34:48.320 --> 00:34:51.220
of steps to is another way.

00:34:51.220 --> 00:34:53.640
But if you can't do anything about it,
if you know they're about to do

00:34:53.640 --> 00:34:57.480
something that you simply can't fix,
warn them.

00:34:57.520 --> 00:35:00.080
Again, user control says let them do it.

00:35:00.130 --> 00:35:02.880
But as this example shows where the
person's about to erase the hard disk,

00:35:02.880 --> 00:35:02.880
you can't do anything about it.

00:35:02.880 --> 00:35:04.720
Again, user control says let them do it.

00:35:04.730 --> 00:35:05.450
But as this example shows where the
person's about to erase the hard disk,

00:35:05.450 --> 00:35:07.480
tell them, "If you do this,
we can't fix it for

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:12.250
you." But when you can,
provide a way for the user to fix it.

00:35:12.510 --> 00:35:15.250
Undo and redo is the simplest way.

00:35:15.380 --> 00:35:20.250
So after a user performs an action,
have an undo choice that allows

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:22.030
them to undo that action.

00:35:22.190 --> 00:35:25.820
And then of course there's the,
"I did this.

00:35:26.100 --> 00:35:27.110
No, I didn't really want to do this.

00:35:27.290 --> 00:35:29.800
Yes,
I do want to do it." So there's redo,

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:31.830
which is an undo of an undo.

00:35:32.220 --> 00:35:36.240
When you need to, provide alerts.

00:35:36.340 --> 00:35:39.980
And we showed you a good alert.

00:35:39.980 --> 00:35:42.590
But if you see that you're
providing a lot of alerts,

00:35:42.680 --> 00:35:46.150
revisit your interface because you're
probably doing something that's

00:35:46.150 --> 00:35:48.100
making it more difficult for the user.

00:35:48.340 --> 00:35:53.530
Alerts are provided when needed,
but you shouldn't see a lot of them.

00:35:56.090 --> 00:35:59.180
Modelessness.

00:35:59.210 --> 00:36:01.690
In general,
don't trap the user into a particular

00:36:02.130 --> 00:36:04.000
mode or way of doing things.

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:05.850
And that's a general rule to follow.

00:36:05.850 --> 00:36:07.340
And the first thing
people are going to say,

00:36:07.340 --> 00:36:09.000
well, there are times when I have to.

00:36:09.170 --> 00:36:10.390
And yes, it makes sense.

00:36:10.390 --> 00:36:14.040
If, for example,
in the real world metaphor

00:36:14.040 --> 00:36:17.680
that you're copying,
the user would be in a mode.

00:36:17.680 --> 00:36:19.780
Let's say in a paint program,
you pick a brush.

00:36:19.780 --> 00:36:21.650
Well, you're in a brush mode now.

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:25.450
But make it visible to the user
how to get out of that mode.

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:28.000
And into the next mode.

00:36:28.150 --> 00:36:31.420
Generally speaking,
you would like the user to be able

00:36:31.420 --> 00:36:33.660
to do whatever they want at any time.

00:36:33.720 --> 00:36:37.760
There are ways to improve the
modelessness of your application.

00:36:37.790 --> 00:36:41.210
And I've listed several here
and we'll go through them.

00:36:41.210 --> 00:36:43.480
One of them is modeless dialogs.

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:47.510
For example, when you're setting
preferences or settings,

00:36:47.510 --> 00:36:49.880
put them in a modeless dialog.

00:36:50.050 --> 00:36:53.250
That way the user can interact
with the--your application

00:36:53.250 --> 00:36:54.580
or other applications.

00:36:54.600 --> 00:36:57.470
And the other advantage
of a modeless dialog,

00:36:57.470 --> 00:37:01.720
such as this utility palette,
is that it allows the user to

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:06.390
see the results of the settings
that they're making immediately.

00:37:06.760 --> 00:37:09.380
Another way that's new
in MacÂ OSÂ X is Sheets.

00:37:09.760 --> 00:37:14.650
They've been around for a while now,
but it may be curious to put that

00:37:14.650 --> 00:37:18.240
as a way of modelessness since
they're essentially modal dialogs.

00:37:18.300 --> 00:37:21.670
The point is they're modal
only to the document or window

00:37:21.670 --> 00:37:23.480
that they're attached to.

00:37:23.580 --> 00:37:26.270
And while they're up,
it allows the user to go to other

00:37:26.380 --> 00:37:29.950
places in your application or other
places in the system and do things.

00:37:30.050 --> 00:37:34.660
So, use sheets as a way of
promoting modelessness.

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:37.040
Another is drawers.

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:42.350
Drawers take possibly big chunks
of the interface that might always

00:37:42.350 --> 00:37:46.660
be in the user's face and allows
the user to display them or not.

00:37:46.730 --> 00:37:49.990
So, they're not stuck in the
mode of always seeing it.

00:37:50.030 --> 00:37:53.230
They can choose whether
or not they want to be,

00:37:53.310 --> 00:37:55.420
to have those things present.

00:37:55.540 --> 00:37:59.940
So, it increases the modelessness
of your application.

